    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically like a neutral middleman. but who usually manages it? is it like a bank or is it a specific person? and how do they actually \"hold\" the money safely until everything is finished?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great questions! The escrow account is typically managed by a neutral third party, often a title company or an escrow agent. In some cases, it could also be handled by a bank or a licensed real estate professional. These entities are specifically trained and regulated to handle such transactions, ensuring that the funds and property are managed securely.\n\nAs for holding the money safely, the escrow agent will deposit the buyer's funds into a secure escrow account. This account is separate from the buyer's and seller's personal accounts, providing an additional layer of protection. The funds can only be accessed once all the terms of the sale are met and the transaction is completed. This way, the money is \"held\" and managed by the escrow agent until everything is in order, ensuring both parties' interests are safeguarded. It's a bit like a secure vault for the transaction, keeping everything under wraps until the deal is finalized.",
      "source": "target",
