      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i get the vault thing. what happens if something goes wrong right at the end though? like if there's a sudden disagreement about the house condition or some paperwork is missing right before we close? does the escrow agent just sit on the money until it's all sorted out?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, the escrow agent plays a crucial role in resolving any last-minute issues that may arise during the closing process. If there's a disagreement about the house condition or missing paperwork, the escrow agent will work to mediate and resolve these issues. They may contact the buyer, seller, and any relevant parties to discuss the problem and find a solution.\n\nIn some cases, the escrow may hold the funds until the issues are resolved, ensuring that neither party is unfairly disadvantaged. However, the exact process can vary depending on the terms of the escrow agreement and the nature of the dispute. It's important to communicate openly with the escrow agent and other parties involved to work towards a resolution.\n\nIf a resolution cannot be reached, legal action may be necessary. The escrow agent will provide guidance on the next steps, but it's always a good idea to consult with a real estate attorney to understand your rights and options in such situations. Remember, the goal of the escrow process is to ensure a fair and smooth transaction, so it's in everyone's best interest to resolve any issues promptly.",
